AN EVENT was held in Pimville, Soweto, yesterday to mark Child Protection Week. Kids from different primary and high schools attended! They were told about the importance of exposing their abusers. Gauteng health MEC Gwen Ramokgopa said at the event: &ldquo;We can&rsquo;t do this on our own. And we need the help of parents and the community at large. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m happy to help wherever I can, and I&rsquo;m honoured to have teams working in my department to make sure pupils are educated about taking care of themselves.&rdquo; The event was held at the kasi&rsquo;s Nike Stadium.Ramokgopa said she was worried about the increasing number of teenagers falling pregnant. She said she felt more could be done to make sure that girls don&rsquo;t fall pregnant. She would work with the department of education to find solutions. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s sad because teenagers are still babies themselves when they suddenly have to look after someone else,&rdquo; said Ramokgopa.- Meanwhile, kids from creches around Dlamini kasi in Soweto marched to Moroka Police Station yesterday to protest against the abuse of women and kids.The protest was organised by Thembi Dlamini (60), the principal of Khayalethu Day Care.She told the People&rsquo;s Paper: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re appealing to communities and the police to watch over our kids.&rdquo; Gauteng social development spokesman Mbangwa Xaba said: &ldquo;We support the march. Creches are important to the development of kids.&rdquo;